This is a SystemC example code of a FIR filter that supports any level of taps.
It contains:
1. FIR.h         - The FIR module declaration
2. FIR.cpp       - The FIR process implementation
5. main.cpp	 - The test bench
6. Makefile	 - The make script to complile the modle
7. README        - This file

To try run this example, first download SystemC 3.0.0 or later from Accellera.

Then modify makefile to fit into your SystemC installation. There are two
variable definitions to modify:
1. SYSTEMC_DIR    : change to your SystemC installation directory
2. CXX            : add -std=c++17 compile flag
3. v3.0.2 & later : add -Wl,-rpath,${SYSTEMC_DIR}/lib to link run-time library

Do 'make' to compile the module. Then run it using './fir'. The result
is stored in a VCD waveform file called RESULT.vcd

Implementation details:
1. void fb_cal() uses sc_fixed and it is not synthesizable. Call this function
inside SC_CTOR is the easiest way to remove it from a synthesizable
implementation.
2. For Nth-order FIR there are N delays (registers.) And sc_signal non-blocking
descriptor must be used to define delays.
3. There are N+1 amplifiers (multipliers) for a Nth-order FIR. And there are
N additions to sum up N+1 terms of multiple. And these computations are
blocking.
4. Do not use STL data structure, e.g. vector, in a synthesizable circuit
design, for STL-like pointer heavy data structures are not synthesizable.
For real circuit designs the most complicated data structure needed is the
C-style array.

This example adds an out-of-spec f16, a 16-order FIR using the default
constructor to test the use of default constructor. This is only for
demonstration and not to meet the spec given.
